ups, and homomorphisms of Lie groups are studied by making use of the Lie algebra. The last chapter is concerned with the theory of compact groups, culminating in Peter-Weyl's theorem on the existence of representations. Given a compact group, it is shown how one can construct algebraically the corresponding Lie group with complex parameters which appears in the form of a certain algebraic variety (associated algebraic group). This construction is intimately related to the proof of the generalization given by Tannaka of Pontrjagin's duality theorem for Abelian groups. The continued importance of Lie groups in mathematics and theoretical physics make this an indispensable volume for researchers in both fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aLie groups. 0aManifolds (Mathematics). 0aTopological groups. 7aMATHEMATICS / Group Theory.2bisacsh  aAdditive group.  aAdjoint representation.  aAlgebra over a field.  aAlgebraic extension.  aAlgebraic variety.  aAlgebraically closed field.  aAnalytic function.  aAnalytic manifold.  aAutomorphism.  aAxiom of countability.  aBall (mathematics).  aCardinal number.  aCharacteristic polynomial.  aCoefficient.  aCommutator subgroup.  aComplex number.  aConnected component (graph theory).  aContinuous function (set theory).  aContinuous function.  aCoordinate system.  aCoset.  aCountable set.  aCovering group.  aCovering space.  aDifferential algebra.  aDifferential calculus.  aDifferential form.  aDifferential of a function.  aDual space.  aEigenvalues and eigenvectors.  aEndomorphism.  aEquivalence class.  aExistential quantification.  aExponential function.  aExterior algebra.  aFundamental group.  aGalois group.  aGeneral topology.  aGeometry.  aGroup (mathematics).  aGroup theory.  aHermitian ma